content.title: Johnson & Johnson: Q4 Earnings Snapshot
content.summary: NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) — Johnson & Johnson (JNJ) on Wednesday reported fourth-quarter net income of $5.12 billion. The New Brunswick, New Jersey-based company said it had net income of $2.10 per share. Earnings, adjusted for one-time gains and costs, came to $2.46 per share.

headline: J&J’s Sales and Profit Rise on Strong Cancer and Autoimmune Drug Sales
summary: Higher sales of drugs for cancer and autoimmune conditions more than offset the sales hit from a key drug patent loss and helped  Johnson & Johnson  report increased revenue and profit for the latest quarter.  J&J said Wednesday that net earnings rose 20.8% in the fourth quarter to $5.12 billion, or $2.10 a share, from $3.43 billion, or $1.41 a share, a year earlier.  Adjusted to exclude certain items such as litigation costs, J&J earned $2.46 a share in the quarter, matching the mean estimate of analysts surveyed by Factset.

Adjusted to exclude certain items such as litigation costs, J&J earned $2.46 a share in the quarter, matching the mean estimate of analysts surveyed by Factset.

headline: A Stock Slump Could Slam the Economy
summary: Yeah, right, sure—we know: “The stock market isn’t the economy.”  The share of U.S. household financial wealth derived from stocks has never been so high, easily exceeding the peak of the tech bubble. headline: Johnson & Johnson Earnings Beat Estimates. The Stock Is Falling.
summary: Johnson & Johnson  stock was falling Wednesday even as the multinational pharmaceutical giant posted better-than-expected earnings for the fourth quarter.  There was one glaring weak point in the print: Sales of Stelara, formerly one of  Johnson & Johnson’s  biggest sellers, cratered 48% in the quarter.  While this partially offset operational sales growth in Johnson & Johnson’s pharmaceutical arm, sales of other products helped soften the blow.
